HTML

	Hyper text markup language
		Used to define structure of a web page (where everything goes)
		organized into elements with opening and closign tags

		<!DOCTYPE html>
		<html>
			<head>
				<title>My Page</title>
			</head>
			<body>
				<img src ="file/location" />
				<p></p>

//FIXME GOOGLE THESE TWO, apparently similar
				<div></div>   (block)

				<span>        (inline)

				<ol>		ordered list
					<li>item1</li>
					<li>item2</li>
				</ol>

				<ul>
				</ul>

				<h1>text</h1>  //headers h6 much smaller

				<a href = "url">link text</a>//links

			</body>

		</html>

	CSS
		Cascade style Sheets
			3 ways to include css:
				1. external style sheet
					html 					css
					//link css
					<a rel = "stylesheet"  	
						href="___.css">		p {
					<body> 			 	 	background-color: 
						<p>Hello all</p>		blue;
					</body> 				}
				2. inline css
					<body>
						<p>Hello all</p>
						<p style="bckgrdcolor = green">Hey</p>
					</body
				3. internal styling (style tag)
					<style>
					</style>

					<body>
					</body>
			Precedence: Internal Styling, Inline Styling, External Style. If you make something green, blue, yellow in internal styling, inline, external, then the thing will be green only

			//this "id" is unique identifier!!
			<p id="first" class="myclass">Cat</p>
			<p id="second" class="myclass">Dog</p>
			Classes can let us do consistent styling
			ID can let us target just one specific thing
			Format: Under CSS for this,
				#first{ style }
				#second{  }
				#third{  }
				.myclass{  }